<a href="https://pubads.g.doubleclick.net/gampad/jump?iu=0&sz=1&c=234" target="_blank"><img src="https://pubads.g.doubleclick.net/gampad/ad?iu=0&sz=1&c=234" border="0" alt=""></a>Their father, Enos Bila (47), said the family was going through a tough time. “We were supposed to be celebrating the birth of our kids, but instead we’re mourning their deaths,” said Enos. “We still don’t know what happened to them, as no one from the hospital has given us an explanation. “I need to know what killed my children because they were born healthy.”Enos said officials at the hospital advised him to cremate the babies. “I refused to burn my children because I wanted to give them a decent funeral,” he said. “I loved my children, despite not having had a chance to hold them in my arms. “Their deaths have torn the family apart as we can’t come to terms with this massive loss.” Khumbuzile Xaba (36), the kids’ mum, said at the time when she was waiting to be discharged so she could take her bundles of joy home, she was not aware they had died.“My family was eagerly awaiting their arrival,” said Khumbuzile.She had even given the kids names – Golden Sphamandla, Gift Siyabonga, Prince Sibusiso and Princess Sphesihle.“No one even had the decency to tell me how or why they had died,” Khumbuzile told the People’s Paper. “I still have unanswered questions. “The pain of losing so many children at once is not going to heal anytime soon.”